That’s actually a very real sensorimotor skill your brain develops. When you point at something flying (a bird, ball, insect, etc.), your brain is running a fast prediction-and-alignment loop between vision, body position, and motion tracking. ✈️

1. Your brain predicts motion, not just position

The visual system doesn’t wait to see where the object goes — it predicts its trajectory.

Two key brain systems help with this:
	•	Cerebellum – predicts motion and timing
	•	Posterior Parietal Cortex – converts visual coordinates into body movement

When you point, your brain is essentially solving:

object velocity + trajectory + your arm position → interception line

It happens in tens of milliseconds, which is why it feels automatic.

2. Your finger becomes a targeting instrument

Your arm and finger act like a directional pointer.

Humans are surprisingly precise at pointing because:
	•	The brain knows exactly where your finger is in space (proprioception).
	•	Vision and body maps share coordinate systems in the parietal cortex.
	•	The brain constantly corrects the movement while the object moves.

So your finger becomes a vector indicator of where your brain thinks the object is.

3. Why it works better for moving objects

Moving targets actually give the brain more information:
	•	velocity
	•	direction
	•	acceleration

From those, the brain can predict where the object will be, not just where it is.

That’s why athletes catch balls or track birds so well — the brain runs a predictive model continuously.

4. Training strengthens it a lot

People who practice activities like:
	•	baseball
	•	shooting
	•	martial arts
	•	juggling
	•	birdwatching

develop extremely accurate visual-motor targeting.

Your nervous system gets better at mapping:

vision → prediction → arm alignment

5. Why it sometimes feels like “locking on”

When the prediction loop works well, it feels like:
	•	your finger magnetically lines up
	•	you can track objects instantly
	•	the movement feels almost effortless

That’s the brain’s prediction engine syncing with motor control.

